{"commentv2": 1, "number": 2, "id": 1821983, "nreplies": 16, "sticky": 0, "user": "Alahuakbar", "body": "After it randomly came to me tonight, I finally realized where the inspiration for Lei Shen's character and backstory came from. He was the first emperor of the Mogu, and he's actually based off the first emperor of China, Qin Shi Huang. Qin was also a bit of a tyrant, he conquered many lands, and was a full time dictator. He conquered all of the separated states of china and unified them under one banner. (Like Lei Shen did to all the races of Pandaria) Qin ordered his army of slaves to do anything and everything for him, and would constantly enslave more and more people to do his bidding. One massive work order he bestowed upon his slaves was actually to create a huge wall to block off barbarian invaders from china, and this wall would later become the Great Wall of China. Sound familiar? Lei Shen constructed the Serpents spine wall for the same purpose, except instead of keeping out barbarians, it was to keep out the Mantid. Finally, even though MANY people tried to assassinate Qin, they all failed due to the Emperor's strength and cunning, and in the end, Qin died a natural death of old age, once again, just like Lei Shen. \r\n\r\nThis is a really cool historical reference by blizzard and it makes me even more excited to face him in the upcoming weeks! :D", "date": "2013-03-05T23:46:46-06:00", "rating": 174, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [{"body": "the terracotta army are also commissioned by Qin Shi Huang as part of his funerary art, and that's why the a lot of questlines in pandaria involve mogu statues coming to life and whatnot.", "creationdate": "2013-03-22T02:01:55-05:00", "id": 644343, "rating": 16, "commentid": 1821983, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "qroxfire", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "Oh my god, qroxfire! Thank you so much for reminding me of that! I knew about Qin's Terracotta Army but I didn't put 2 and 2 together a few weeks ago when I made this comment. There's absolutely no doubt that Lei Shen is based off Qin Shi Huang, because he ordered the stone molds of each of his soldiers to be made to guard his body in his burial Vault, which would be an extension of his will left behind to protect him. Since many of the stone Mogu enemies names say they are Terracotta, it appears the Mogu and the Will of the Emperor in Mogushan Vaults are all based off on Qin's final order!", "creationdate": "2013-03-24T15:56:26-05:00", "id": 645132, "rating": 5, "commentid": 1821983, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Alahuakbar", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "Well, he wasn't poisoned by his alchemists, he ended up poisoning himself by consuming a poisonous metallic element, because he was trying to find a way to gain immortality, and thought this metal could help him do so. That being said, he was VERY old by this time, so he would have died soon at that point anyways. The point is though, he still didnt die by anyone else's hand but his own, so no one ever truly defeated him throughout his very long lifespan.", "creationdate": "2013-05-16T22:21:00-05:00", "id": 659122, "rating": 3, "commentid": 1821983, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Alahuakbar", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "Whoops, meant to say: He personally thought that the element would give him immortality, nobody actually knew it was poisonous yet, so the alchemists told him to give it a try since their entire careers and lives depended on helping their emperor. So he wasn't intentionally poisoned, and he basically poisoned himself.", "creationdate": "2013-05-16T22:29:01-05:00", "id": 659123, "rating": 2, "commentid": 1821983, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Alahuakbar", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "The references don't end there, either. Much like Lei Shen, Qin brought in a single language policy, defined a book of laws, standardised weights and measures and created a single currency. It seems also that he destroyed books and killed scholars so nobody could talk smack about him in writing. Oh, wait, Lei Shen did that too?", "creationdate": "2014-01-08T19:42:50-06:00", "id": 720249, "rating": 2, "commentid": 1821983, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "LanceofAbel", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}}
{"commentv2": 1, "number": 3, "id": 1823064, "nreplies": 4, "sticky": 0, "user": "DorianFyre", "body": "[b]Lei Shen[/b], otherwise known as [b]The Thunder King[/b], was the first Emperor of the Mogu. He unified the mogu races into one giant clan rather than many divided clans and through his will many of Pandaria's most notable works of ancient architecture were created, including the Serpent's Shine, Mogu'shan Palace and the two shrines either side of it in the Vale. He also lay the foundations for a dynasty of Mogu emperors, ruling an empire of slaves.\n\nThe mogu are a power-hungry race whose history is written in the blood of their enemies. In the past, warring clans and kingdoms fought for dominion over parcels of land, each looking to gain the upper hand against their neighbors. That all changed when Lei Shen leveraged his power and cunning to became the greatest of the mogu. Born during the Age of a Hundred Kings, Lei Shen was the son of a warlord and possessed a strength that commanded respect from the other mogu. He went on to do what many thought impossible; he united the mogu kings beneath him and declared himself emperor.\n\nOnce united, the mogu swept across Pandaria, conquering and subjugating all of the other races\u2014until he encountered the mantid. The Lorewalkers were diligent in chronicling the history of Pandaria and have this text on record:\n\n[quote][i]'It has been written that when the great Lei Shen first looked upon the lands of the mantid, he did not feel fear, but inspiration.\n\nAs he began to unify his people under a single banner and subjugate the other races of Pandaria, he knew that the mantid would never succumb to his authority. They spoke his language, the language of strength. He commanded his slaves to construct the Serpent's Spine, a magnificent wall that spanned the length of the empire.\n\nIt would take many generations to build. But Lei Shen knew how to motivate his subjects. Fear. Fear of the mantid moved mountains, raised armies, secured his empire, and built his wall.'[/i][/quote]\n\nHe is rumoured to have died of natural causes, as during his time, none could stand up to his might. He was taken to a mogu crypt deep within Kun Lai Summit, and entombed. It was and still is a great honor for mogu to be buried intact, as they otherwise treat the corpses of their dead as as parts and reagents for their spells and magic. \n\nHowever, the departure of the mists has prompted the return and rise of the Zandalari trolls, who have brought The Thunder King back to life. It falls to the Alliance and Horde's strength to put him down, as the forces of Pandaria alone are regrettably not enough.\n[quote]\n\n[i]Pandaria, her hills of gold,\nIn dark and mournful times of old,\nDid once a hopeless horror hold.\nWhen from her sacred Vale did spring,\nWith storm and flash, a monstrous thing,\nHis name Lei Shen, the Thunder King.\nHis thunder boomed across the land,\nAnd none who dared and fought could stand\nAgainst the iron tyrant\u2019s hand.\nA palace grand, a walled domain,\nSuch mighty works born of his reign.\nBuilt by slaves, their hearts in chains,\nBut seasons change and tyrants die,\nHis fury spent in times gone by,\nThe thunder slept beneath Kun-Lai.\nBy Zandalari hands he has been taken,\nBy Zandalari voice he has awakened.\nGather heroes, sound the drums,\nThe Thunder King comes...\n[b]The Thunder King comes.[/b]\n[/i][/quote]\n\n[b]But most importantly of all, [u]he is voiced by the one-and-only Christopher Lee[/u] - though you might know him better as Sauron the White, from The Lord of the Rings films.[/b]", "date": "2013-03-06T19:00:29-06:00", "rating": 61, "indent": 0, "roles": 0, "deleted": 0, "outofdate": 0, "userRating": 0, "replies": [{"body": "The voice actor is actually Paul Nakauchi, check imdb", "creationdate": "2014-11-16T16:11:32-06:00", "id": 790862, "rating": 7, "commentid": 1823064, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Naszamax", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "Naszamax is correct. Blue confirmation: http://us.battle.net/wow/en/forum/topic/18000366894#18", "creationdate": "2015-06-12T01:01:49-05:00", "id": 874650, "rating": 4, "commentid": 1823064, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "maeltum", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "I know we have 2 voices acting for Lei Shen one only on the ptr and one other on the live game PTR one : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7HH_iZBwwSA Live : https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=at525Ung6Hg I'm pretty sure the voice for the live game is played by Christopher Lee", "creationdate": "2015-10-02T01:39:44-05:00", "id": 902302, "rating": -1, "commentid": 1823064, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "Zalendra", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}, {"body": "Actually, Not any reference of Wow in the Christopher Lee datas on IMDB. And it is NOT Sauron The White, it's Saruman the White, Sauron being the Evil one who forged the Ring. So, obviously, Sir Lee dubbed the characters that he played in films, as Sarumane the White, Franscico Scaramanga, but also pure game characters or narrator as in Kingdom Hearts II, EverQuest II, Freelancer, and more, but NOT WoW !", "creationdate": "2019-12-27T13:29:48-06:00", "id": 1345007, "rating": 1, "commentid": 1823064, "dataTree": 1, "roles": 0, "username": "ludo1800", "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "downvotedByUser": false, "reportedByUser": false, "votedByUser": false}], "dataTree": 1, "markupDisabledEnvironments": {"ptr": true, "beta": false}, "lastEdit": ["2014-09-08T09:05:10-05:00", 2, "DorianFyre"]}
